<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-584-317  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 584 317.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  Nov 1990 v7 n11 p80(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The joy of automatic data updates. (live data exchange in UNIXsystems)(includes related articles on 'hot data,' graphical userinterfaces)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hayes, Frank.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many new UNIX applications incorporate the concept of 'live data,'which allows linking together of programs and documents so that adocument is automatically updated whenever its associated data ischanged.andP;  Conventional data processing relies on a singlecentralized database, but distributed UNIX systems encouragemaking copies of files; keeping up with the current versions ofevery drawing in a large technical document can be very difficult.andO;Frame Technology's FrameMaker 2.0 has a Live Links feature thatcan link a document with an illustration and reflect changes inthe document automatically.andP;  Interleaf's Active Documenttechnology is a more ambitious example of live linking; documentsconsist of small embedded programs that include data links andprograms that fine-tune data.andP;  Live links reduce the tedium ofupdating documents, but a user reviewing a linked document mustcheck both the text and the links.andP;  Next-generation graphicalenvironments such as HP's NewWave and Next Inc's NextStep offerbuilt-in support for live links.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Interprocess CommunicationTrendsSoftware DesignUNIXDocument Management SystemsDesktop Publishing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>